metadata.name: Obliques #247
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Scalabili-TREE  #25
metadata.description:
Scalabili-TREE 
Growing up and adapting to the world!

For the Decentralized Autonomous Education (https://linktr.ee/cubiclearn) (DAE) project they asked me to represent the concept of "scalability" with an artwork.
Scalability is one of the ten principles on which the DAE project is based. The other nine principles were represented by nine other artists.

To represent the concept of scalability in a visual way, with a generative algorithm, I was inspired by nature and plants.
I represented this concept through the growth rings of trees, drawing shapes that evoked the section of a cut tree. Each ring represents the growth of the tree and its ability to adapt to the environment while continuing to function efficiently.
This can involve a variety of different strategies, for example the tree can increase root depth and branch out to support a larger canopy, or develop mechanisms to conserve water and nutrients to survive in a dry environment
One key aspect of scalability in trees is the ability to adapt to changing environmental conditions over time.

The work was created through the construction of a generative algorithm that designs each ring starting from the center, gradually adding the outer layers, exactly as the tree itself would do.

Everything is generated with code.
This work uses p5.js library and c2.js library.

metadata.name: let me fall #172
metadata.description:
A study of form, empty spaces, panic attacks, asymmetry, tinnitus, chaos, and the never-ending journey to obtain imperfection. 

30 Matisse-inspired palettes.

2-6 – increase resolution.

“f” – add more noise to iteration at current resolution.
“n” – redraw at current resolution without noise.
“s” – save export.

Please be patient while drawing at higher resolutions, it can take quite a while.

Created with p5js.

metadata.name: Echoes #33
metadata.description:
"The stars were also temporal travelers. How many of these ancestral flashes of light were echoes of long-gone suns? And how many awaited their birth, whose brightness had not yet reached us? If all the suns were to fade away, except for ours, how long would it take for us to realize our solitude? I always knew that the firmament harbored mysteries, but only now do I understand that the earth is also shrouded in enigmas."

Project created in p5.js
Press "s" to save the image.

metadata.name: Make-believe #4
metadata.description:
#genuary32nd – Let's meet on this make-believe date, in this make-believe place.
I’m having déjà vu, or is it a memory?

This artwork is originally created for the genuary2023 prompt "Art Deco", using the same core algorithm as Memory Module. Made with fractal math and p5js.

Keyboard controls:
[s] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[g] Toggle texture.

URL params:
&aspect=[aspect ratio, eg 2]
&res=[resolution multiplier, 0.5-8]

Created by Elsif, 2023.02

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #80
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: CHX-1 #170
metadata.description:
Glitching pixels like it’s 1999.

Inspired by 90’s digital aesthetics, CHX-1 takes a random selection of GAN seeds, combines them in unique ways, and processes them –individually and as a group– with a series of glitching dithering algorithms. Generating fun, original, colorful artworks. Millions of possibilities. Have fun!

<<< Base seeds generated offline using personal styleGAN2-ADA models. Image processing and combinations done generatively by the CHX-1 algorithm >>>

GAN –> p5js –> Blockchain


• Artworks can take a few seconds to load when running live code.

• Press “s” (when "open live" is active) to save a PNG image.

metadata.name: a reveure! #88
metadata.description:
‘a reveure!’ is a catalan farewell expression. this collection is a souvenir to celebrate me meeting up with artists, collectors and friends during 2023’s summer art events (Responsive Dreams in Barcelona and NFT Show Europe in Valencia). 
mechanics to get a piece: say ‘hi’ and chat with me to get a free pass to mint your iteration and its signed miniprint. i’ll be doing mobile live minting on small screen (iPad/phone) during Barcelona and Valencia events. 

‘a reveure!’ is about simplifying my painting brushes style used in previous works, in an attempt to find minimalist and more conceptual approach. using only black and white and minimizing the use of random, i explore the void and the spaces generated on the canvas, discovering how abstract sculpture-like figures emerge. raw edges and big brushes make the eye confused as it seems 3D shapes building up. 

this line of work and the concept behind it was inspired by Elena Asins’ computer art from late XX’s century.

the motion restarts every 20sec
press [s] or click/touch to save an image
press [r] to reload 
press [1] - [9] to make higher resolution
press [c] to make brushes spin
press left/right arrows to move brushes left/right

made with love and p5js

thank you fxhash team to give me the opportunity and tools to do this special mobile live minting

Marc L Clapers / mekhno
summer 2023
